{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516402"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:42:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:42:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12614"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12614"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.05,0.16,0.76,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5100"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77719"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5100"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63235"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"166"},{"type":"tags","id":"1267"},{"type":"tags","id":"1838"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8535"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9074"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77719"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with a three month history of episodic pruritis, upper abdominal pain and jaundice. On these occasions she has noticed dark urine and pale stools. The patient has a history of ulcerative colitis, which has been effectively managed with medication for the past five years. Blood tests reveal an elevated alkaline phosphatase level, and an ultrasound examination shows dilatation of the intrahepatic bile ducts. A subsequent magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP) is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Autoimmune hepatitis","Cholangiocarcinoma","Choledocholithiasis","Primary sclerosing cholangitis","Viral hepatitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Epatient\u0027s history of ulcerative colitis, persistent itching, jaundice, elevated alkaline phosphatase level; together with the MRCP findings of beading of the right main bile ducts are consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary sclerosing cholangitis\u003C/strong\u003E (PSC). PSC is a chronic liver disease characterised by inflammation and scarring of the bile ducts and it is strongly associated with inflammatory bowel disease, particularly UC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Eautoimmune hepatitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause elevated liver enzymes and jaundice, the patient\u0027s presentation and MRCP findings are not typical for autoimmune hepatitis. Autoimmune hepatitis would generally not cause the specific bile duct changes seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Echolangiocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E (bile duct cancer) can cause similar symptoms and is a possible complication of primary sclerosing cholangitis, the overall clinical picture and MRCP findings are more suggestive of PSC. Cholangiocarcinoma would typically present with more localised bile duct abnormalities and may have additional imaging findings, such as a mass or irregular wall thickening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst gallstones in the biliary tree (\u003Cstrong\u003Echoledocholithiasis\u003C/strong\u003E) can cause right upper quadrant pain, jaundice and changes in urine and stool colour, the findings of elevated alkaline phosphatase, bile duct dilation, and strictures on the MRCP are more consistent with a different diagnosis. Dilatation of the biliary tree would be more in keeping with choledocholithiasis. Gallstones would typically be visible on ultrasound, which was not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause jaundice and elevated liver enzymes, the patient\u0027s presentation and MRCP findings are not typical for viral or autoimmune hepatitis. Viral hepatitis would generally not cause the specific bile duct changes seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary sclerosing cholangitis is a chronic liver disease characterised by inflammation and scarring of the bile ducts, and it is strongly associated with inflammatory bowel disease, particularly ulcerative colitis."],"references":["Rawla P, Samant H. Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis. [Updated 2023 Feb 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537181/","Lazaridis KN, LaRusso NF. Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis. N Engl J Med. 2016 Sep 22;375(12):1161-70. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra1506330. PMID: 27653566; PMCID: PMC5553912. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5553912/","Rabiee A, Silveira MG. Primary sclerosing cholangitis. Transl Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2021 Apr 5;6:29. doi: 10.21037/tgh-20-266. PMID: 33824933; PMCID: PMC7829069. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33824933/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63235"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12614"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19972"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19972"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/sto